%S A397486 25,26,29,97,98,99,100,132,804,805,806,807,808,809,810,812,813,814,
%T A397486 815,816,817,828,990,991,992,993,994,1562,1563,1564,1565,1572,1573,
%U A397486 1574,1575,1578,1579,1580,1581,1582,1583,1596,1597,1598,1599,1628,1629,1630,1631,1667
%N A397486 Numbers k such that log(g(k)) > gpf(g(k)), where g is A000793 and gpf is A006530.
%C A397486 Remark 56 on page 33 of the Deléglise and Nicolas reference gives the wrong direction of the relation.
%H A397486 Hugo Pfoertner, <a href="/A397486/b397486.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..3272</a>, (terms for g(k<=10^6)).
%H A397486 Marc Deléglise and Jean-Louis Nicolas, <a href="https://cs.uwaterloo.ca/journals/JIS/VOL18/Deleglise/deleglise3.html">On the Largest Product of Primes with Bounded Sum</a>, Journal of Integer Sequences, Vol. 18 (2015), Article 15.2.8.
%e A397486 a(1) = 25 is in the sequence because g(25) = A000793(25) = 1260 = 2^2*3^2*5*7; log(1260) = 7.1388669999... > 7.
%e A397486 27 is not in the sequence because g(27) = 1540  = 2^2*5*7*11; log(1540) = 7.3395... < 11.
%Y A397486 Cf. A000793, A006530.
